00:01:41.980 --> 00:01:47.360
Most scholars agree that playing cards were invented in Imperial China as early as the 9th century Tang Dynasty.

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:50.280
These cards were originally based on paper currency of the time.

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:56.440
But because using real money was inconvenient and risky, they substituted play money known as money suited cards.

00:01:56.440 --> 00:02:02.460
There were two varieties -- Lut Chi, from the south of China that used four suits, and Kwan Pa'i, that had a heavy focus on coin imagery.

00:02:02.460 --> 00:02:07.720
By the 13th century, the Persians had ganjifeh, which was probably introduced by the Mongols or traded on the Silk Road.

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:10.800
And then the Mugals brought these cards to India in the 16th century.

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:15.460
In India, the cards took on a circular shape that kind of looked like the game POG from the 90s.

00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:21.140
And, moving further west, the Egyptians had a card game known as mamluk, which arrived sometime during the 12th or 13th centuries.

00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:26.560
These ornately hand-painted cards were of Islamic origin and named after the Mamluk Sultanate of Egypt.

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:32.260
A complete 15th century pack contained four suits -- polo sticks, coins, swords, and cups --

00:02:32.260 --> 00:02:36.480
and three additional court cards -- king, vice king, and second vice king.

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:43.040
Gaming scholar David Parlett claims that "Egypt's mamluk entered Southern Europe in the 14th century," which is just one of many theories.

00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:48.840
But what we do know for sure is that France's King Charles VI purchased three packs of playing cards in 1392.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:53.580
These cards featured similar imagery to the mamluk cards with cups, swords, coins, and batons,

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:59.180
but also had 22 extra high cards that eventually became tarot cards used by mystics for divination.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:03.420
And as playing cards travelled to many European countries, their suits evolved with them.

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:06.220
The Italians had cups, coins, clubs, and swords.

00:03:06.220 --> 00:03:08.960
The Germans had hearts, bells, acorns, and leaves.

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:13.940
It was the French who created the established suits we know today -- hearts, diamonds, clubs, and spades.

