00:03:27.620 --> 00:03:30.080
Poker is one of the most well-known betting games.

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:35.960
Poker can trace its ancestry back to the 16th century, with the Spanish game of primero, nicknamed "poker's mother".

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:43.400
By the 17th century, the French had a popular betting game known as poque, and by the 18th century, Germans had a similar game called pochen.

00:03:43.400 --> 00:03:48.380
These two games established betting and bluffing mechanics that would become a key component to modern poker.

00:03:48.380 --> 00:03:54.160
French colonists brought poque to Canada, which then followed immigrants as they travelled down the Mississippi River to New Orleans.

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:57.760
It eventually spread throughout the country and gaming parlors on river boats.

00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:03.020
It was growing rapidly in popularity and in 1834, Jonathan H. Green (different John Green)

00:04:03.020 --> 00:04:08.140
wrote that this new cheating game was dominating the boats and replacing the popular Three-card Monte games,

00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:11.440
and went on to coin the term poker in his book on gaming.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:15.240
And the game of poker continued to spread, becoming a staple in Western saloons.

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:22.640
Poker had continued to increase in popularity, spawning versions like seven card stud and Texas hold 'em, solidifying its place within the gambling community.

00:04:22.640 --> 00:04:27.660
Now, before I reach modern times, we should also briefly cover the origin of trading card games.

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:33.900
Trading card games are defined as games that are mass produced to be purchased and incorporated within a player's deck for strategic play.

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:40.800
The first real trading card game, or TCG, was the baseball card game, published in 1904 by the Allegheny Card Company.

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:46.820
The game consisted of 104 player cards that deck builders could supposedly collect to compete within the game.

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:52.220
But because this game was only a prototype and never mass produced, the deck-building component was never fully realised.

00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:56.780
1993 saw the first modern trading card game -- Magic: The Gathering.

00:04:56.780 --> 00:05:00.140
Invented by game designer and math professor Dr Richard Garfield,

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:04.860
the entire initial 2.6 million print run sold out within the first month,

00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:10.440
encouraging the publisher, Wizards of the Coast, to print another 7.3 million cards before its official release.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:15.680
Another 35 million cards would be printed between 1993 and 2007.

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:25.140
And as of 2015, there are 13,651 different cards in 11 languages, attracting an estimated 20 million players.

00:05:25.140 --> 00:05:30.000
In 1996, the Pokemon trading card game was released in Japan by Media Factory.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:38.020
Now, there were other Pokemon sets before this, but this was the first set based on the Pokemon video games, and would eventually be brought to the US in 2003.

00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:45.920
As of 2015, there are a total of 125 Pokemon trading card game sets and nearly 15 billion of these cards have been produced worldwide.

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:50.760
There is even an official Pokemon League, where players can compete against others in their community.

00:05:50.760 --> 00:06:00.640
And the Pokemon card game is so popular that it switched roles and became the inspiration for several Pokemon card game video games, including Pokemon TCG Online and Pokemon Card GB2.

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:02.740
So what makes the TCGs so popular?

00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:11.660
Well, Mark Rosewater, the head designer for Magic: The Gathering, said that it was the player's ability to customise and personalise their decks with a near endless supply of cards for success.

00:06:11.660 --> 00:06:17.100
He said, "If you compare it to something like Monopoly, every time you play you're getting a pretty similar experience."

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:20.240
"But what's neat about Magic is that the game itself keeps changing."

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:22.900
"It's about exploring, and you get to constantly rediscover it."

00:06:22.900 --> 00:06:25.140
And people have certainly continued to discover it.

00:06:25.140 --> 00:06:31.080
According to 2008 sales data, trading card games earn around $800 million just in North America.

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:34.280
But it's not just the sales and prevalence of these games that make them significant.

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:36.360
They are also having an impact on our lives.

00:06:36.360 --> 00:06:46.780
Human-computer interaction assistant Professor Geoff Kaufman from Carnegie Mellon conducted a study in 2015 that used a new research method, known as embedded game design, in a series of card games.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:54.320
Kaufman wanted to see if he could decrease gender biases in people by including pro-equality messages in card games without making those messages too blatant.

00:06:54.320 --> 00:07:01.240
He found that his games were encouraging people to have increased social identity complexity, which is basically a measure of tolerance in groups.

00:07:01.240 --> 00:07:04.700
Players tended to think more broadly and inclusively about social groups.

00:07:04.700 --> 00:07:08.720
They also had stronger and more assertive responses to multiple kinds of social bias.

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:12.220
Basically, the games encouraged participants to embrace diversity.

00:07:12.220 --> 00:07:20.200
It may not always be as obvious in a game like Pokemon TCG or Yu-Gi-Oh!, but the study helps to show the small role card games may play in bringing people together.

00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:24.060
